in several ELISA tests was designated as virus free and the extracts were pooled and used as a diluent and as an antigen in some titrations. Individual samples were analysed on 30 to 60% (w/w) sucrose gradients in SET buffer at 9000o g for 3 h. Light-scattering bands containing virus were removed, pooled, diluted with SET buffer and sedimented at 6o000 g for 30 rain. The virus was resuspended in SET buffer, clarified at 4000 g for 5 min and aliquots of approx. 0"5 mg virus (A2,o of 5) were stored at - 9 o ° C .
Protein determinations. Protein concentration was estimated by the method of Lowry et al. 095I); bovine serum albumin was used as a protein standard.

Preparation of antisera
Primary antibodies. Guinea-pigs were immunized by injecting 2 aliquots, each of approx, o'5 nag virus mixed with Freund's complete adjuvant, intraperitoneally at a 7 day interval. The animals were exsanguinated by heart puncture 3 weeks later and a crude IgG fraction was obtained by precipitation with ammonium sulphate (4o %, w/v).
Secondary antibodies. Rabbits were immunized intramuscularly with four samples each of approx, o'5 mg of virus in SET buffer at 7 day intervals. The complement-fixing titre of the serum against Io #g/ml O. rhinoceros baculovirus was I/I28o. To produce pure unabsorbed IgG the serum was incubated on columns containing CNBr-activated Sepharose 4B (Pharmacia) linked with donkey anti-rabbit IgG. After thorough washing, the rabbit IgG was eluted with o-2 M-glycine-HCl buffer, pH 2.2. The concentration of rabbit IgG was estimated spectrophotometrically, assuming A°;~0~a = I'4. For use in the majority of tests, to ensure that the IgG preparations did not react with insect protein, the unfractionated serum was first absorbed with an extract of virus-free larvae. Then, 2.o ml of serum were incubated with 0"5 ml of virus-free insect extract at 37 °C for 3 h and centrifuged at ioooo g for 30 min before incubation on immunoadsorbent Sepharose columns.
Tertiary antibodies. Goat IgG specific for rabbit IgG and linked with alkaline phosphatase was obtained from Miles Research Products, Miles Laboratories, Elkhart, Ind., U.S.A. and was used without further purification at a dilution of I/IOOO.
Indirect ELISA technique. The assays were performed in polystyrene microtest plates (MTP. I, Australian Disposable Products Pty, Ltd., Adelaide, South Australia). Coating, substrate, rinsing and sample buffers are described by Flegg & Clark 0979) and our indirect ELISA method is based on the procedures described by Clark & Adams (1977). Plates were coated with ioo #1 primary antibody at 2 to 5 #g/ml for 48 h at 37 °C and reacted with IOO #1 antigen diluted in sample buffer, for 6 h at 37 °C. Then IOO/~1of secondary antibody was added at 0"5 to 2/~g/ml for 16 h at 37 °C and followed by IOO/~1of conjugated tertiary antibody for 4 h at 37 °C. Finally 200 #1 of substrate (p-nitrophenyl phosphate), at 0"5 mg/ m l , was added and the plate was incubated at 37 °C for at least 90 min. The reaction was stopped by adding 50 #1 of 2 M-NaOH. The absorbance at 405 nm of the coloured reaction product was measured after diluting each sample to 0.8 ml. All assays were performed in duplicate.

RESULTS
Up to 5 mg of Oryctes virus were obtained from faecal samples from each infected adult beetle. The enveloped virus particles were relatively fragile and there was some loss of virus during gradient purification. Therefore, only one cycle of purification of virus was carried out and in the subsequent development of an ELISA method two factors had to be considered. First, that there might be antibodies to insect protein in the immune sera and second, that the immune sera might also react non-specifically with insect protein. Methods

